[center][b][size=4]This is a 1.0 candidate in active testing. If you play it, PLEASE send feedback or bug reports, and include the MAO.log from that session[/size][/b]
[i](Documents\My Games\Skyrim Special Edition\SKSE\MAO.log)[/i][/center]
[line]

A load-order mod that replaces single-use potions with permanent, reusable [i]flasks[/i]. Instead of brewing consumables that vanish on use, you gather abstracted [i]essence[/i] in the field, learn effect [i]blueprints[/i] by analyzing potions you find, and configure a small kit of flasks you refill and re-use forever. Vendors stop selling potions; the world's potions become the recipes you unlock. The perk tree and the ingredient economy are calibrated to your actual load order, so whatever list you play, the numbers fit it — nothing is hardcoded.

Built entirely on Linux with no Creation Kit and no xEdit: the plugin is generated byte-by-byte from Python, the install-time patcher is a Mutagen/.NET (Synthesis) tool, and the SKSE plugin builds on GitHub Actions.

[size=5][b]Features[/b][/size]

[b]Flasks, not potions[/b] — your kit holds a few permanent flasks (2–6, perk-scaled), each configured with a discovered blueprint and holding 2–9 charges. Drink one and the effect fires instantly, the flask stays, and a charge is spent. Dry flasks refill themselves from your pouch when you sleep or on a background timer. Flasks have no gold value — they're kit hardware, not merchandise.

[b]Essence, not inventory[/b] — harvesting flora or looting creatures never fills your bags with ingredients. The native layer intercepts the pickup and increments a three-tier essence currency — Base, Catalyst, and Apex — in an abstracted Alchemical Pouch. Boss-tier drops feed the Apex tier; common flora feed the Base tier.

[b]Blueprints from the world[/b] — potions stay in enemy drops, boss chests, and hand-placed loot. Pick one up and it's analyzed in place: the single-use item is destroyed, and you're awarded a permanent blueprint for that effect plus essence matching its tier. You can't configure a flask for an effect until you've found its physical counterpart, so exploration gates capability.

[b]Two economies, one toggle[/b] — a single MCM switch flips the whole system live. [b]Essence mode[/b] (default) spends pouch essence to fill flasks. [b]Ingredient mode[/b] converts nothing: your ingredients and potions stay as normal items, and a flask charge instead costs its variant's recipe ingredients out of your bags. The two economies are mirror images, priced the same way; blueprint learning works in both.

[b]Weapon coatings[/b] — offensive blueprints become timed weapon coatings once you take the Vanguard Coating perk: a real, sustained duration (45 seconds, or 120 with Corrosive Retention) applied with standard vanilla poison rules — no clunky "drink your poison" state. Without the perk, offensive blueprints can be found but not prepared.

[b]An alchemy tree rebuilt for the kit[/b] — the load order's alchemy perk tree is rewritten in place: a Kit Calibration ladder that adds flask slots and charges, essence-efficiency and cost-reduction nodes for the Apex tier, and coating perks. Progression buys [i]capacity and efficiency[/i], not raw magnitude — standalone MAO never scales past your list's own standard potion caps. Perks that don't touch crafting (Snakeblood, Green Thumb) are kept as-is and stack with MAO's.

[b]Calibrated to your load order[/b] — the install-time patcher reads your actual list and (a) rebuilds whichever alchemy tree WINS your load order, and (b) sorts every ingredient into Base/Catalyst/Apex tiers by real rarity and value. The result suits vanilla, Requiem, LoreRim, or a heavy overhaul list alike.

[b]The Field Kit[/b] — a native menu (multiple skins, full controller support) opened by taking over any alchemy station. It shows your essence stores, your flask slots and their charges, and your known blueprints, and lets you reconfigure a flask anywhere out of combat. Configuration and tuning live in the MCM.

[size=5][b]Requirements[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]SKSE64[/*]
[*]Address Library for SKSE Plugins[/*]
[*]SkyUI[/*]
[*]MCM Helper[/*]
[*][url=https://github.com/Mutagen-Modding/Synthesis]Synthesis[/url] — MAO ships a Synthesis patcher that rebuilds the perk tree and calibrates the ingredient tiers to your load order (see Install). Synthesis carries its own .NET requirement, so there's nothing extra to install for MAO.[/*]
[*]No DLC required (they only add more ingredients and potions to the pool if present).[/*]
[/list]
Developed and tested on Skyrim SE 1.6.1170 against a Requiem-based list (LoreRim) and a pure-vanilla Steam Deck install. The bundled MAO.dll is part of the mod and required.

[size=5][b]Install[/b][/size]

[b]1.[/b] Install the package with your mod manager near the end of the load order, and enable [b]MAO.esp[/b].

[b]2.[/b] Adapt MAO to your load order with [b]Synthesis[/b] (there's no exe to run):
[list]
[*][b]Easiest:[/b] download the [b]MAO.synth[/b] file (in Optional Files), then in Synthesis select a group and double-click it — it adds the MAO patcher for you, with the correct project already selected.[/*]
[*][b]Or manually:[/b] add a Git Repository patcher pointing to [url=https://github.com/marthofdoom/MAO]github.com/marthofdoom/MAO[/url], and select the project [i]installer/MAO.Synthesis/MAO.Synthesis.csproj[/i].[/*]
[/list]
Run your Synthesis pipeline. It reads YOUR load order, rebuilds the alchemy perk tree (writing [i]MAO - Patch.esp[/i]), and writes your calibrated ingredient tiers ([i]mao_tiers.json[/i]) — no separate patch esp to manage by hand.

[b]3.[/b] Enable the Synthesis output in your load order (Synthesis normally does this for you) and play. Re-run Synthesis after any load-order change.

[b]No Synthesis?[/b] MAO is still fully playable without the patcher: the DLL auto-grants the flask perks at their skill thresholds (you just don't spend points on Alchemy), and ingredient tiers fall back to a built-in name heuristic. Running Synthesis upgrades both to your actual list — it's strongly recommended, not mandatory.

No FOMOD — the options are runtime MCM toggles. Upgrades are save-safe within a major line: flask, essence, and blueprint state lives in the SKSE co-save and migrates itself on load.

[size=5][b]Experimental / maybe-working[/b][/size]

Two pieces are shipped honestly as unfinished — they won't break anything, but don't count on them yet:
[list]
[*][b]Automated-potion-mod compatibility[/b] — flasks are tagged as potions, so some auto-potion utilities may recognise them, but the dedicated compatibility layer (inventory-count faking, a consumption intercept) is [i]not built yet[/i]. Treat it as unverified and likely partial at best.[/*]
[*][b]Fluid Motion perk[/b] — detects whether you run a drink-animation mod and disables itself when none is present. The detection is live; the actual movement-penalty reduction lands when a specific target mod is identified. Until then the perk is inert by design.[/*]
[/list]

[size=5][b]FAQ[/b][/size]

[b]Does this just make me overpowered?[/b]
No. Standalone MAO never scales magnitudes past your load order's own standard potion caps — it changes where potions come from, not how strong the list lets them be. Reaching those caps unperked is deliberately expensive (it burns raw Apex essence at a punishing rate); perks buy kit capacity and efficiency, not bigger numbers.

[b]Will it work on my modlist?[/b]
That's the point of the patcher — it rebuilds whichever alchemy tree wins your load order and derives the ingredient tiers from the mods you actually run, so it fits vanilla and heavy overhauls (Requiem, LoreRim) alike.

[b]Do I have to run Synthesis?[/b]
It's strongly recommended but not mandatory. Without it MAO auto-grants perks by skill and tiers ingredients by a name heuristic. With it you get the rebuilt perk tree and tiers calibrated to your list.

[b]Can I turn parts off or tune it?[/b]
Yes. The essence/ingredient economy toggle, gather and cost rates, and the rest are MCM sliders and toggles.

[b]What happens to potions I already have or find?[/b]
Found potions are analyzed into blueprints as you pick them up (in ingredient mode they're studied but kept). Vendors no longer stock single-use potions.

[size=5][b]Roadmap[/b][/size]

The core system is here: flasks, essence gathering, blueprint discovery, the rebuilt perk tree, coatings, and the two-economy toggle. Current directions:

[b]Full auto-potion compatibility[/b] — field-verify and finish the automated-consumption contract against the popular utilities.

[b]Fluid Motion[/b] — wire the movement-penalty reduction to a confirmed drink-animation mod.

[b]A learning-mode toggle[/b] — choose between find-to-learn and recipe-item learning for blueprints.

[b]Deeper overhaul integration[/b] — over-cap magnitude scaling gated behind a companion Requiem framework, for lists that want the late-game power fantasy.

